# Backend rules (server/)

When editing or adding code under `server/`, follow these rules.

## 1. No unwanted comments
- Do not add comments unless they clarify non-obvious behavior or critical business logic.
- Prefer clear names and small functions over comment blocks.

## 2. Null checks and try/catch
- Add null/undefined checks before using values that may be missing.
- Wrap risky operations (I/O, parsing, external calls) in try/catch and handle errors explicitly.
- Do not leave empty catch blocks; log or rethrow as appropriate.

## 3. Optional chaining and optional parameters
- Use optional chaining when accessing nested or possibly undefined values, e.g. `data?.label`, `user?.profile?.name`.
- Use optional parameters and default values where it makes sense instead of manual undefined checks.

## 4. Proper error handling
- Handle errors at the right layer (e.g. route handlers, service boundaries).
- Return consistent error shapes and HTTP status codes.
- Avoid swallowing errors; log and/or propagate so failures are visible and debuggable.

## 5. Reuse existing code
- Before writing new logic, search the codebase for existing utilities, helpers, or similar logic.
- Prefer importing and reusing rather than duplicating. Refactor shared logic into shared modules if needed.

## 6. Clean and understandable codebase
- Keep functions small and focused.
- Use clear, consistent naming and structure so the code is easy to read and maintain.

## 6a. Utils and types per module
- Put validation helpers and type guards in the module’s util file (e.g. `video.utils.ts`), not in controllers.
- Put constants and shared types/interfaces in the module’s types file (e.g. `video.types.ts`).
- Controllers should only handle request/response and delegate to services or utils; keep no inline validation or constant definitions there.

## 7. Proper types (no `any`)
- Use explicit types for variables, function parameters, and return values.
- Do not use `any`; use proper types, interfaces, or generics.
- Rely on TypeScript for type safety; define or import types instead of escaping with `any`.

## 8. Playwright tests for new functionality
- When adding or changing functionality under `server/`, add or update Playwright tests that cover that behavior.
- Integrate the test into the existing test suite so it runs in CI/local checks.

## 9. JSDoc for util functions
- Add short, clear JSDoc for every utility function (parameters, return value, and a one-line description).
- Keep JSDoc minimal and accurate; avoid redundant or noisy comments.
